12. First Step in GATE Preparation

Made a timeline with proper order of subjects.

Followed his college curriculum sequence:

1st year → EDC, electrical basics

2nd year → Signals & Systems

Used that order to complete GATE syllabus.

13. Best Free & Paid Resources

Used:

College notes

Physics Wallah (Parag batch)

Gabate / Gateopedia for PYQs

NPTEL videos for some concepts

14. Short Notes Strategy

Did not make traditional short notes.

He always scribbled ideas on rough sheets because:

Writing helps retain concepts longer

But those scribbles were not meant for revision later.

15. Easiest Revision Strategy

Revised from:

Notes

Gateopedia summaries

Gateopedia contains:

Concise summaries of all concepts of each subject.

He started serious revision in Nov–Dec of 3rd year.

16. Test Series Strategy (Very Unique)

He never bought any paid test series.

Used:

Only the FREE test series on GATE official website

Attempted PYQs from 2020 onwards only in last 20–30 days

He intentionally held them back to:

Get realistic score estimation

Simulate real exam pressure

17. Last 2 Months – Handling Demotivation

He did not get demotivated, because he enjoys problem-solving.

If a mock test went bad:

He refreshed his mind

Analyzed mistakes

18. How He Analyzed Tests

While analyzing:

For tough questions: skip during exam, but during analysis:

Study solution

Identify concept

Detect patterns

Check if he was missing something fundamental

His observation:

If basics + intuition are strong, scoring 55+ becomes easy.

19. Tips for Finishing Exam Faster

When reading a question:

Spend 10–20 seconds judging difficulty.

Solve in shifts:

Easy

Medium

Lengthy

Difficult

If a question takes more than 3–4 minutes, skip it.

20. Tips on Improving Accuracy

Stay mentally sharp during exam.

Intuition can sometimes be wrong; always verify.

One example:

Intuition gave a wrong answer; detailed reading gave correct answer.

21. Handling Exam Nervousness

Initially nervous, but he reminded himself:

These are just problems

He enjoys solving them

Shifted mindset from fear → enjoyment.

22. His Exam Hall Mindset

He did not expect AIR 1.

Expected:

Before exam: top 100

After exam: under 50

Low expectations helped reduce nervousness.

23. His Next Plan After GATE

Gave GATE to judge himself as an engineer.

Wants to:

Join a private company

Pursue Masters/PhD through the company if allowed

Why judge himself?

Topping college is at university level

GATE is pan-India level, a better benchmark.

